        <title>Overview</title>
        <contents>&lt;h2 style="text-align: left;"&gt;Unit 4: Incorporating Instruction in Critical Thinking at All Levels of Adult English Language Acquisition*&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;This unit focuses on critical thinking skills as well as the language of critical thinking adult English language learners, in any type of class at any level, need to:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul style="text-align: left;"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Express ideas and build on others' ideas in academic and professional conversations appropriately&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Access and understand more complex written and oral texts at work and school&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Make use of higher-order skills to make decisions, solve problems, and fully engage with others&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Content in this unit complements the content in Units 2 and 3, as well as in the other modules in the LINCS ESL Pro Project.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium; color: #a0271d;"&gt;*The &lt;em&gt;Workforce Innovation and Opportunities Act&lt;/em&gt; uses the term &lt;em&gt;English Language Acquisition&lt;/em&gt; (ELA) to describe English language instruction for nonnative English speakers rather than the ESL or ESOL terminology.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;Listen to audio:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;a href="@@PLUGINFILE@@/ELL_MOD1_UNIT4_0010.mp3"&gt;ELL_MOD1_UNIT4_0010.mp3&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;details&gt;&lt;summary&gt;Audio transcript&lt;/summary&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Welcome to Unit 4 of Meeting the Language Needs of Today’s Adult English Language Learner. In this unit, we turn to critical thinking. What are critical thinking skills and why are they so important? Also, how do learners express those critical thinking skills in their speaking and writing? Critical thinking is closely linked to understanding complex texts and tasks as learners analyze and interpret information.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This unit complements Units 2 and 3 and represents one of the core components of meeting the language needs of today’s adult ELLs. It should take between 2 and a half and 3 hours to complete. Continue to the unit objectives now.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/details&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;em&gt;Using the buttons at the bottom will present the materials in order. &lt;/em&gt;&lt;em&gt;You can also navigate to the pages in this section by using the &lt;/em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Lesson menu&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;em&gt; on the left.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</contents>
